Anonymous Wed 15 May 2024 11:17:22 No.65759610 Report
Quoted By: >>65761331
>>65759496
One suggestion that may or may not be helpful to you, but I've found useful myself, it to try something small and fun first. If you've got a character more or less thought out, then do an exercise writing a short where the character goes somewhere and does something fun. This could be say, she goes to a bar. Is she there alone or with a friend? While there perhaps she crosses paths with a guy/girl/whatever who joins them. While they are drunkenly having a laugh together then think why is this other person there? What about the other patrons? Are they soldiers on leave? Seedy types in a dive?
While writing the fun shenanigans they get up to it might open up lines of thought on the wider world around the characters. I'm not suggesting a 20,000 word autism explosion or anything, but trying to force your mind to hammer down big world building points can tire you out, while something short and fun can maybe get the creative juices trickling, if not flowing.
I might just be talking out of my ass and you find it not remotely helpful, but this is just my two cents anyway.
Hope you get through it.
